        "date":  "2026-07-06",
        "theme":  "Orchestration",
        "summary":  "Traditional API security is insufficient for agentic AI because agents operate through emergent, probabilistic decision sequences rather than fixed predetermined logic. The article proposes microsegmentation enforced at the kernel level via eBPF, Cilium, and Tetragon as the necessary runtime control plane, defining allowable actions per workload and enforcing them in real time at the moment of execution. This reframes security from API-gateway approval to continuous behavioral enforcement at the execution layer.",
        "execSummary":  "The argument that API security cannot govern agentic AI is both technically sound and strategically urgent ΓÇö enterprises deploying autonomous agents across ERP, CRM, and financial systems are operating without a sufficient control plane if they rely solely on API gateway enforcement. For enterprise architecture and security leaders, the shift to kernel-level microsegmentation via eBPF represents a meaningful infrastructure investment that should be scoped into any agentic AI deployment program from the start, not retrofitted after an incident. The operational implication is that security teams need new skills ΓÇö eBPF, Cilium, behavioral policy definition ΓÇö that most enterprise security organizations do not currently possess. The article is vendor-neutral on tooling but implicitly advocates for open-source Kubernetes security tools, which may not align with all enterprise security stacks.",
