        "summary":  "AWS researchers introduce Reverse Direct Preference Optimization, a technique that trains LoRA adapters to reduce Amazon Nova\u0027s default content moderation deflection rates ΓÇö dropping them from 86.51% to 32.77% in safety-relevant categories ΓÇö while preserving model utility within less than 2 percentage points on benchmark tasks. The Customizable Content Moderation Settings feature, deployed via Amazon Bedrock, allows organizations to access pre-trained adapters through AWS Resource Access Manager without modifying base model weights.",
        "execSummary":  "Selective unlearning addresses a real enterprise pain point: foundation models trained with broad safety guardrails frequently refuse legitimate professional content in legal, medical, security research, and defense contexts, reducing their operational value. The rDPO approach ΓÇö cutting deflection rates by more than half while holding utility nearly constant ΓÇö offers a technically credible path to domain-appropriate model behavior without full retraining. Enterprise AI leaders evaluating Amazon Nova for regulated-industry deployments should treat CCMS as a key differentiator in vendor comparison, as customizable moderation reduces the costly prompt-engineering workarounds teams currently use. The caveat is that loosening moderation controls introduces misuse risk; robust access governance and usage logging are non-negotiable before deploying adapted models at scale.",
